{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/lung-pleural-cancers-recognition-referral/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"9ea3734a-4640-5249-855d-86a7092ebddf","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 85fd0854-dc39-4287-b327-90812dbdf662 --><h1>Lung and pleural cancers - recognition and referral: Summary</h1><!-- end field 85fd0854-dc39-4287-b327-90812dbdf662 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item b12afd3f-d80f-40e8-aac7-f85bcfd840d2 --><!-- begin field e7712b91-cf37-4235-9d0f-e5fa35222fc3 --><ul><li>Over 43,000 new lung cancers are diagnosed each year in the UK. A full time GP is likely to diagnose approximately one person with lung cancer each year. The 5-year survival is below 10%.</li><li>Refer people using a suspected cancer pathway referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for lung cancer if they:<ul><li>Have chest X-ray findings that suggest lung cancer, or</li><li>Are aged 40 years and over with unexplained haemoptysis.</li></ul></li><li>Offer an urgent chest X-ray (to be performed within 2 weeks) to assess for lung cancer in people aged 40 years and over if they have two or more of the following unexplained symptoms, or if they have ever smoked and have one or more of the following unexplained symptoms:<ul><li>Cough.</li><li>Fatigue.</li><li>Shortness of breath.</li><li>Chest pain.</li><li>Weight loss.</li><li>Appetite loss.</li></ul></li><li>Consider an urgent chest X-ray (to be performed within 2 weeks) to assess for lung cancer in people aged 40 years and over with any of the following:<ul><li>Persistent or recurrent chest infection.</li><li>Finger clubbing.</li><li>Supraclavicular lymphadenopathy or persistent cervical lymphadenopathy.</li><li>Chest signs consistent with lung cancer.</li><li>Thrombocytosis.</li></ul></li><li>Over 2500 new mesotheliomas are diagnosed each year in the UK, though the incidence is increasing rapidly. Most are pleural, though peritoneal mesotheliomas also occur. A full time GP is likely to diagnose approximately 2–3 people with mesothelioma in their career. The 5-year survival is below 10%.</li><li>Refer people using a suspected cancer pathway referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for mesothelioma if they have chest X-ray findings that suggest mesothelioma.</li><li>Offer an urgent chest X-ray (to be performed within 2 weeks) to assess for mesothelioma in people aged 40 years and over, if they have two or more of the following unexplained symptoms, or one or more of the following unexplained symptoms and have ever smoked, or one or more of the following unexplained symptoms and have been exposed to asbestos:<ul><li>Cough.</li><li>Fatigue.</li><li>Shortness of breath.</li><li>Chest pain.</li><li>Weight loss.</li><li>Appetite loss.</li></ul></li><li>Consider an urgent chest X-ray (to be performed within 2 weeks) to assess for mesothelioma in people aged 40 years and over with either:<ul><li>Finger clubbing, or</li><li>Chest signs compatible with pleural disease.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field e7712b91-cf37-4235-9d0f-e5fa35222fc3 --><!-- end item b12afd3f-d80f-40e8-aac7-f85bcfd840d2 -->","topic":{"id":"7d8c9378-296e-5faf-9c97-f97a7697364d","topicId":"2a330e0f-ed6b-480c-bb50-2b5e80aec564","topicName":"Lung and pleural cancers - recognition and referral","slug":"lung-pleural-cancers-recognition-referral","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"9ea3734a-4640-5249-855d-86a7092ebddf","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"df6756d2-9d89-5e47-9f87-390ace3c2f88","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"18a8d7b0-cc8b-52a5-bf11-5b539d78052d","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"ddf9ce79-381f-532e-a153-7a53082b9dfc","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"f3370663-425b-5c3e-a6fe-ad8d1be96f25","slug":"update","fullItemName